{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Jay Belsky | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|07|07}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | pronounce = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = American | fields = [[Child psychology]] | workplaces = [[University of California-Davis]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[Cornell University]] (Ph.D., 1978) | thesis_title = Family interaction in toddlerhood: a naturalistic observational study | thesis_url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Family_interaction_in_toddlerhood.html?id=1-dPAAAAYAAJ | thesis_year = 1978 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Work on effects of [[child care]] on children | influences = | influenced = | awards = 1988 Boyd McCandless Award, 2007 Urie Bronfenbrenner Award, 2015 Bowlby-Ainsworth Award | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Jay Belsky''' (born July 7, 1952)<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L-tPAAAAYAAJ |title=The short term stability of mother-infant interaction within and across two settings: home and laboratory |last=Belsky |first=Jay |date=1976 |publisher=Cornell University, Sept. |pages=ii |language=en}}</ref> is an American child psychologist and the Robert M. and Natalie Reid Dorn Professor of [[Human development (psychology)|Human Development]] at the [[University of California, Davis]]. He is noted for his research in the fields of [[child development]] and [[family studies]]. He was a founding investigator of the [[NICHD]] Study of Early Child Care and Youth Development in the [[United States]], and of the National Evaluation of [[Sure Start]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://humandevelopment.ucdavis.edu/people/jay-belsky |title=Jay Belsky |website=Human Development Graduate Group |language=en |access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref> He has been an [[ISI Highly Cited Researcher]] since 2002.<ref name="waimh">{{Cite web |url=http://www.waimh2018.org/skeakers-biographies/ |title=Jay Belsky |website=WAIMH 2018 |language=en-GB |access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref>
==Career== After receiving his Ph.D. from [[Cornell University]] in 1978, Belsky joined the faculty of [[Penn State University]], where he became a distinguished professor of human development before leaving the faculty there in 1999. From 1999 to 2010, he was a professor of psychology at [[Birkbeck University of London]], where he was also the founding director of the Institute for the Study of Children, Families and Social Issues. He became the Robert M. and Natalie Reid Dorn Professor of Human Development at the University of California, Davis in 2011. Since 2010, he has been a member of the [[Academy of Europe]].<ref name=waimh/>
==Research== Belsky has published multiple studies reporting that [[child care]] is associated with an increased risk of psychological and behavioral problems for children. These studies have been covered extensively by the media,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/2001/04/26/belsky |title=Jay Belsky doesn’t play well with others |last=Sweeney |first=Jennifer Foote |date=2001-04-26 |website=Salon |language=en |access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Shell |first=Ellen Ruppel |date=1988-08-01 |title=Babes in Day Care |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/past/docs/issues/88aug/babe.htm |magazine=The Atlantic |access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref> though they have been criticized by some other researchers. One such critic, Kathleen McCartney of the [[University of New Hampshire]], said in 1987 that "None of the studies Jay [Belsky] talks about look at the quality of child-care arrangements or the family backgrounds".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/25/us/day-care-for-infants-debate-turns-to-long-term-effects.html |title=Day Care for Infants: Debate Turns to Long-Term Effects |last=Collins |first=Glenn |date=1987-11-25 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-09-28 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Partly as a result of the controversy provoked by a study he published in 1986, he later left the United States to work in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/oct/02/nurseries-childcare-pre-school-cortisol |title=The great nursery debate |last=Gentleman |first=Amelia |date=2010-10-01 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2017-09-28 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>
